<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="405" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,670,854,880]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Description of the terminal instar larva</emphasis>
. Material examined: 
<collectingCountry box="[911,1010,854,880]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1022,1110,854,880]" country="Bulgaria" name="Plovdiv" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Plovdiv</collectingRegion>
, Dzhendem tepe, 
<quantity box="[1312,1386,854,881]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" unit="m" value="165.0">165 m</quantity>
, larvae extracted from galls found in 
<taxonomicName box="[529,748,890,916]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Hypecoum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imberbe">
<emphasis box="[529,748,890,916]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Hypecoum imberbe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; galls collected 
<date box="[930,1083,890,917]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" value="2001-05-19">19 May 2001</date>
. A Sojanova leg. (n=4)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" box="[199,805,926,953]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,926,952]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Description:</emphasis>
length 
<quantity box="[431,517,926,953]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" unit="mm" value="2.7">2.7 mm</quantity>
(range 
<quantity box="[602,733,926,953]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.65" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" unit="mm" value="2.65" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.3">2.3 – 3 mm</quantity>
; n=4).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
Body in ventral view fusiform, segments of larval body widest approximately around the middle, tapering towards the anterior and posterior ends (
<figureCitation box="[612,703,998,1024]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,345,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-80@13.[151,1435,345,1933]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Fumariphilus hypecoi, n. comb., SEM photos of a terminal instar larva. (A) Body, ventral view. (B) Body, lateral view. (C) Head, anterior view. (D) Detail of mouth parts. (E) Right mandible. (F) Left mandible." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683392" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683392/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
); in lateral view more clearly tapering towards the posterior end (
<figureCitation box="[160,249,1034,1060]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,345,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-80@13.[151,1435,345,1933]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Fumariphilus hypecoi, n. comb., SEM photos of a terminal instar larva. (A) Body, ventral view. (B) Body, lateral view. (C) Head, anterior view. (D) Detail of mouth parts. (E) Right mandible. (F) Left mandible." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683392" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683392/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
). Integument smooth, almost bare and with a yellowish orange coloration (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1199,1034,1061]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1519,1543]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1495]" captionTargetId="figure-18@7.[151,1436,181,1495]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Habitus, forewing and terminal instar larvae of Fumariphilus hypecoi, n. comb. (A), (C), (E) and Fumariphilus versicolor, n. comb. (B), (D) and (F). All in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683384" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683384/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
). Body composed of head and 13 segments: three thoracic, nine abdominal and one anal. First thoracic segment appears, in ventral view, divided into three parts, one anterior and one posterior that is further sub-divided into two lateral and one medial; first abdominal segment slightly constricted and narrower than the third thoracic segment; abdominal segments 2–5 similar in length and progressively narrower towards the anal segment; anal segment short, truncated at the apex and wider than long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis box="[199,260,1250,1276]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[275,361,1250,1276]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,345,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-80@13.[151,1435,345,1933]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Fumariphilus hypecoi, n. comb., SEM photos of a terminal instar larva. (A) Body, ventral view. (B) Body, lateral view. (C) Head, anterior view. (D) Detail of mouth parts. (E) Right mandible. (F) Left mandible." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683392" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683392/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
) more or less triangular, medial area of vertex slightly sunken. Antennal areas and antennae not visible. Antennal setae absent. A pair of very short and inconspicuous genal setae present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis box="[199,330,1322,1348]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Mouthparts</emphasis>
. Clypeus (
<figureCitation box="[449,535,1322,1348]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,345,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-80@13.[151,1435,345,1933]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Fumariphilus hypecoi, n. comb., SEM photos of a terminal instar larva. (A) Body, ventral view. (B) Body, lateral view. (C) Head, anterior view. (D) Detail of mouth parts. (E) Right mandible. (F) Left mandible." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683392" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683392/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
) well marked with its ventral margin straight and clearly prolonged ventrally into a sub-rectangular piece above the labrum; pair of supraclypeal setae present. Labrum sub-trapezoidal with slightly convergent sides; apical margin straight, pairs of ventrolateral and medioapical short setae present. Mandibles covered by the labrum but apex visible. Maxillae triangular with its apex pointed and with two pairs of maxillary palps and two pairs of maxillary setae present. Labium large, diamond shaped or rhomboidal; salivary opening situated under a rhomboidal depression; the area surrounding the salivary opening present a tuberculate sculpture. Labial palps and labial setae present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis box="[199,317,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Mandibles</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[334,475,1574,1600]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,345,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-80@13.[151,1435,345,1933]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Fumariphilus hypecoi, n. comb., SEM photos of a terminal instar larva. (A) Body, ventral view. (B) Body, lateral view. (C) Head, anterior view. (D) Detail of mouth parts. (E) Right mandible. (F) Left mandible." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683392" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683392/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Figs. 8E, 8F</figureCitation>
) Smooth and bare. Both mandibles with three teeth; the second middle tooth slightly blunt and being as long as half of the large apical tooth in the left mandible; the second tooth of the right mandible blunt and subdivided into two small teeth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis box="[199,376,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Gall structures:</emphasis>
One or more seeded sections of the fruits are considerably inflated. Each galled fruit contains from one to three oval to globose, unilocular galls.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis box="[199,461,1754,1780]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Host plant association:</emphasis>
Galls are formed in the fruits of 
<taxonomicName box="[831,1039,1754,1780]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis box="[831,951,1755,1780]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Hypecoum</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1054,1182,1754,1781]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1912,1936]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,275,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-65@10.[151,1436,273,1889]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Galls of Fumariphilus versicolor, n. comb on Fumaria officinalis (A, B). (C) Section of a galled fruit showing a larva. (D) Section of a mature fruit with a fully developed adult inside. (E) Galls of Fumariphilus hypecoi, n. comb. on Hypecoum procumbens. (F) Section of a mature fruit with a fully developed adult inside." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683388" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683388/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Figs. 6E, F</figureCitation>
). Galls in fruits of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Hypecoum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imberbe">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Hypecoum imberbe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[481,577,1790,1816]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
form a conspicuous swelling on the fruit.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="405" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,299,1826,1852]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Biology:</emphasis>
Life cycle is typically univoltine, as in most herb gall wasps. In the studied material, all reared individuals were females, except for 
<specimenCount box="[548,654,1862,1889]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
. Adults emerge from the galls from the end of winter to early spring, around the time the host plant starts flowering. The larvae overwinter inside the galls and pupate a little before emergence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="406" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,602,2033]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1436,150,321]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="406" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,355,1970,1996]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Distribution:</emphasis>
Originally described from Tripoli (North Africa) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Trotter, A." box="[946,1107,1970,1997]" pageId="12" pageNumber="405" pagination="210 - 219" refId="ref11847" refString="Trotter, A. (1913) Contributo alla conoscenza delle galle della Tripolitania. Marcellia, 11 (4), 210 - 219." type="journal article" year="1913">Trotter (1913)</bibRefCitation>
, its distribution extends from the Eastern Mediterranean (
<collectingCountry box="[458,546,2006,2032]" name="Algeria" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Algeria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[556,655,2006,2032]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[665,746,2006,2032]" name="Greece" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Greece</collectingCountry>
) to Transcaucasia (
<collectingCountry box="[958,1060,2006,2033]" name="Armenia" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Armenia</collectingCountry>
) and Central Asia (
<collectingCountry box="[1270,1428,2006,2033]" name="Turkmenistan" pageId="12" pageNumber="405">Turkmenistan</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Nieves-Aldrey, J. L. &amp; Melika, G." box="[159,510,150,177]" pageId="13" pageNumber="406" pagination="2525 - 2535" refId="ref11352" refString="Nieves-Aldrey, J. L. &amp; Melika, G. (2005) Aylax hypecoi in Europe; redescription with taxonomical and biological notes (Hymenoptera, Cynipidae, Aylacini). Journal of Natural History, 39 (27), 2525 - 2535. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930500105242" type="journal article" year="2005">Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika 2005</bibRefCitation>
). More recently, it was cited from 
<collectingCountry box="[896,976,151,177]" name="Turkey" pageId="13" pageNumber="406">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Katilmis, Y. &amp; Kiyak, S." box="[991,1260,151,177]" pageId="13" pageNumber="406" pagination="2161 - 2167" refId="ref10566" refString="Katilmis, Y. &amp; Kiyak, S. (2008) Checklist of Cynipidae of Turkey with a new genus record. Journal of Natural History, 42 (31 - 32), 2161 - 2167. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930802148981" type="journal article" year="2008">Katilmis &amp; Kiyak 2008</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Katilmis, Y. &amp; Kiyak, S." box="[1272,1329,151,177]" pageId="13" pageNumber="406" pagination="17 - 19" refId="ref10615" refString="Katilmis, Y. &amp; Kiyak, S. (2011) New records of herb gallwasps (Hymenoptera, Cynipidae, Aylacini) from Turkey. North Western Journal of Zoology, 7 (1), 17 - 19." type="journal article" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry box="[1391,1436,151,177]" name="Iran" pageId="13" pageNumber="406">Iran</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Melika, G. &amp; Karimpour, Y." box="[159,466,187,213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="406" pagination="268 - 277" refId="ref10808" refString="Melika, G. &amp; Karimpour, Y. (2012) Herb gallwasp fauna of Iran (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae, Aylacini). North-western Journal of Zoology, 8 (2), 268 - 277." type="journal article" year="2012">Melika &amp; Karimpour 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="406" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,150,321]" pageId="13" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,223,249]" pageId="13" pageNumber="406">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Trotter. Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2005" box="[327,444,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Aylax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hypecoi">
<emphasis box="[327,444,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="406">F. hypecoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
morphologically resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nieves-Aldrey" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Nieves-Aldrey" baseAuthorityYear="1985" box="[771,915,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Fumariphilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="versicolor">
<emphasis box="[771,915,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="406">F. versicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its general appearance and variable coloration. However, the two species can be easily distinguished by the diagnostic characters given in the identification key of the species of 
<emphasis box="[388,548,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="406">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nieves-Aldrey" authorityYear="2022" box="[388,544,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Fumariphilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Fumariphilus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
